 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aVisual Media and the Healthy Self in the 20th Century brings together new research from leading scholars from Europe and North America working at the intersection of film and media studies and social and cultural history of the body. The volume focuses on visual media in the twentieth century in Europe and the U.S. that informed and educated people about life and health as well as practices improving them. Through a series of in-depth case studies, the contributors to this volume investigate the relationships between film/television, private and public actors of the health sector and economic developments. The book explores the performative and interactive power of these visual media on individual health understandings, perceptions and practices. Visual Media and the Healthy Self in the 20th Century aims to better understand how bodily health has evolved as a form of capital throughout the century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aHealth educationxAudio-visual aids. 4aContemporary Society. 4aFilm, Media, and Communication. 4aHealth and Medicine. 4aMedia Studies. 4aPhilosophy. 7aMEDICAL / Public Health.2bisacsh  abody history, health, film history, media studies, visual culture, economic history.1 aBerlivet, Luc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonah, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonah, Christian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBoon, Timothy M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCantor, David, 